Reason: The basic unit for the target compound structure is the benzene ring, which typically has a melting point of 5.5 °C. There are several substituent groups in this case that impact the melting point. In this compound, we have chloro, methoxy, methyl, and fused ring systems (such as cyclohepta and furan rings). Chloro groups typically increase the melting point due to their electronegativity and polarizability, we estimate this increase by +40 °C. Methoxy groups make the compound more polar and can participate in dipole-dipole interactions which might increase the melting point but to a lesser extent than chloro, we estimate this increase by +20 °C. The effect of the methyl group is smaller since it adds hydrophobic character and slightly increases molecular weight, estimated at +5 °C per methyl group, and we have two of them. The fused ring systems add rigidity to the compound and significantly increase the melting point; we estimate this combined effect to increase by +100 °C. So we add all the increments to the benzene base melting point: 5.5 (base) + 40 (chloro) + 20 (methoxy) + 10 (2 methyls) + 100 (fused rings) = 175.5 °C.
